<subSubSection type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageNumber="13">
[[ 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33218" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla apicalis (Latreille)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apicalis">Pachycondyla apicalis</taxonomicName>
species complex ]]
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="discussion">
<subSection type="multiple">
<paragraph pageNumber="13">Species boundaries</paragraph>
</subSection>
<paragraph pageNumber="13">
The morphological evidence considered in conjunction with geography supports the separation of the 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33218" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla apicalis (Latreille)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apicalis">P. apicalis</taxonomicName>
complex into three species. All three are broadly sympatric from northern South America to southeastern Brazil, and the two more common species, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33218" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla apicalis (Latreille)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apicalis">P. apicalis</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:186243" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla verenae (Forel)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="verenae">P. verenae</taxonomicName>
, co-occur in Central America north to southern Mexico (Fig. 11). It is notable that every record of the rarer species 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33337" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla obscuricornis Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obscuricornis">P. obscuricornis</taxonomicName>
involves sympatry with 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33218" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla apicalis (Latreille)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apicalis">P. apicalis</taxonomicName>
(2 sites), 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:186243" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla verenae (Forel)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="verenae">P. verenae</taxonomicName>
(2 sites), or both (3 sites). Furthermore, 29 of 81 records of 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33218" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla apicalis (Latreille)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apicalis">P. apicalis</taxonomicName>
(35.8%) show sympatry with at least one of the other two species, and 29 of 60 records of 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:186243" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla verenae (Forel)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="verenae">P. verenae</taxonomicName>
(48.3%) indicate sympatry as well. This pattern is likely to be an underestimate of local sympatry given that many records result from haphazard hand collecting and not from thorough myrmecological surveys. Sites that have been extensively surveyed (e.g., La Selva Biological Station in Costa Rica and the 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Mbaracayú">Mbaracayu</normalizedToken>
Reserve in Paraguay) usually uncover at least 2 of the species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageNumber="14" pageNumber="13">
Figures 12-17 illustrate some of the morphometric differences among these species. These differences are consistent across the entire range of the 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33218" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla apicalis (Latreille)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apicalis">apicalis</taxonomicName>
complex, including a number of sites where two or more species locally coexist. In particular, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33337" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla obscuricornis Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obscuricornis">P. obscuricornis</taxonomicName>
consistently has shorter antennal scapes than 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33218" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla apicalis (Latreille)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apicalis">P. apicalis</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:186243" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla verenae (Forel)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="verenae">P. verenae</taxonomicName>
(Figs. 12, 13), a relatively broader head (Fig. 14), and a more pubescent hypopygium (Fig. 8). 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33218" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla apicalis (Latreille)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apicalis">Pachycondyla apicalis</taxonomicName>
can be separated from 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:186243" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla verenae (Forel)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="verenae">P. verenae</taxonomicName>
by a taller petiolar node (Fig. 17), by a broader head (Fig. 16), by the lack of strong margination of the petiolar node, by the coloration of the antennal apices, and in South America (but not Central America) by the more extensive pilosity. 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33218" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla apicalis (Latreille)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apicalis">Pachycondyla apicalis</taxonomicName>
is usually larger in most measurements than 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:186243" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla verenae (Forel)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="verenae">P. verenae</taxonomicName>
, but there is enough overlap that size alone is not always diagnostic. Given the strength and consistency of the morphological differences across multiple instances of sympatry, significant gene flow between these species is unlikely.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="14">
The common species 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:186243" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla verenae (Forel)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="verenae">P. verenae</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33218" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla apicalis (Latreille)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apicalis">P. apicalis</taxonomicName>
both show considerable variation across their ranges in a number of characters, including petiole shape, head shape, scape length, eye size, and pilosity. This variation is either localized or broadly allopatric over a north-south cline, and thus in spite of the overall amount of variation there appears to be no justification for further division of the complex. In contrast, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33337" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla obscuricornis Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obscuricornis">P. obscuricornis</taxonomicName>
shows almost no variation across its range, suggesting a recent origin or a population bottleneck.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="14">
Phylogenetic relationships among the three species are unknown. Some characters, such as antennal scape length and hypopygial pubescence, suggest a closer relationship between 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33218" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla apicalis (Latreille)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apicalis">P. apicalis</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:186243" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla verenae (Forel)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="verenae">P. verenae</taxonomicName>
, while others, such as mesosomal and petiolar configuration, indicate a relationship between 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33337" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla obscuricornis Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obscuricornis">P. obscuricornis</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33218" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla apicalis (Latreille)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apicalis">P. apicalis</taxonomicName>
. Molecular genetic data will likely provide the most satisfactory resolution to the problem. Given the variation in the life-histories of these ants (e.g., monogyny in 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33218" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla apicalis (Latreille)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apicalis">P. apicalis</taxonomicName>
and polygyny in 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:186243" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla verenae (Forel)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="verenae">P. verenae</taxonomicName>
) and the amount of published biological information, a phylogeny could be of great utility.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="14">Nomenclature</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="14">
The amount of nomenclatural confusion in this complex is surprising considering the small number of species involved. Latreille (1802) described two similar species from South America, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:134312" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Formica" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Formica flavicornis Fabricius" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavicornis">Formica flavicornis</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:147699" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Formica" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Formica apicalis Latreille" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apicalis">F. apicalis</taxonomicName>
. I have not seen type specimens of either, but the description of the shape of the node and the coloration of the antennal apices leaves little doubt about the identity of 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33218" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla apicalis (Latreille)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apicalis">apicalis</taxonomicName>
, a conclusion also reached by Brown (1957). The identity of 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:134312" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Formica" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Formica flavicornis Fabricius" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavicornis">flavicornis</taxonomicName>
is not as clear. The name 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:134312" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Formica" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Formica flavicornis Fabricius" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavicornis">flavicornis</taxonomicName>
is preoccupied by an older Fabricius (1798) species, and Forel (1905) provided 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:142090" authority="Emery" authorityName="Emery" class="Hexapoda" family="Formicidae" genus="Neoponera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Neoponera latreillei Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="latreillei">Neoponera latreillei</taxonomicName>
as a replacement name. Brown (1957) placed 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:134312" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Formica" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Formica flavicornis Fabricius" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavicornis">flavicornis</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:142090" authority="Emery" authorityName="Emery" class="Hexapoda" family="Formicidae" genus="Neoponera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Neoponera latreillei Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="latreillei">latreillei</taxonomicName>
as a synonyms of 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33218" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla apicalis (Latreille)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apicalis">apicalis</taxonomicName>
on the basis of antennal coloration, a decision that I see no reason to challenge.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="14">
Emery was alone among previous workers in correctly recognizing three distinct entities, although he misapplied the name 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:147699" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Formica" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Formica apicalis Latreille" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apicalis">apicalis</taxonomicName>
. In his 1890 paper “Voyage de M. E. Simon au Venezuela”, he discussed a form with a strongly marginate petiolar node (“ 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:147699" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Formica" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Formica apicalis Latreille" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apicalis">apicalis</taxonomicName>
”), a form with a more rounded node and yellow antennal tips (“ 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:186734" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla flavicornis (Fabricius)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavicornis">flavicornis</taxonomicName>
”), and a new variety of 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:186734" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla flavicornis (Fabricius)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavicornis">flavicornis</taxonomicName>
with dark antennal tips (“ 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:141777" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla flavicornis var. obscuricornis Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="variety" species="flavicornis" variety="obscuricornis">obscuricornis</taxonomicName>
”). Material determined by Emery in MHNG confirms that these names correspond to 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:186243" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla verenae (Forel)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="verenae">P. verenae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33218" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla apicalis (Latreille)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apicalis">P. apicalis</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33337" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla obscuricornis Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obscuricornis">P. obscuricornis</taxonomicName>
, respectively. Emery was content to keep the two forms with the more rounded node as varieties of a single species rather than as separate species, so he placed 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:141777" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla flavicornis var. obscuricornis Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="variety" species="flavicornis" variety="obscuricornis">obscuricornis</taxonomicName>
as a variety of 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:186734" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla flavicornis (Fabricius)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavicornis">flavicornis</taxonomicName>
, and later 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:239973" authority="Emery" authorityName="Emery" class="Hexapoda" family="Formicidae" genus="Neoponera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Neoponera obscuricornis var. latreillei" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="variety" species="obscuricornis" variety="latreillei">latreillei</taxonomicName>
as a variety of 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:239059" authority="Emery" authorityName="Emery" class="Hexapoda" family="Formicidae" genus="Neoponera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Neoponera obscuricornis" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obscuricornis">obscuricornis</taxonomicName>
in “Genera Insectorum ” (Emery 1911) once Forel (1905) proposed 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:142090" authority="Emery" authorityName="Emery" class="Hexapoda" family="Formicidae" genus="Neoponera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Neoponera latreillei Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="latreillei">latreillei</taxonomicName>
as a replacement name for the preoccupied 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:134312" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Formica" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Formica flavicornis Fabricius" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavicornis">flavicornis</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="15">
Forel’s handling of the group parallels Emery’s but is less consistent. Examining the Forel collection at MHNG, I found that Forel largely followed Emery’s treatment of the species with the marginate node as 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33218" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla apicalis (Latreille)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apicalis">apicalis</taxonomicName>
and that with the yellow antennal apices as 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:134312" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Formica" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Formica flavicornis Fabricius" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavicornis">flavicornis</taxonomicName>
/ 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:142090" authority="Emery" authorityName="Emery" class="Hexapoda" family="Formicidae" genus="Neoponera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Neoponera latreillei Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="latreillei">latreillei</taxonomicName>
. Forel also provided new names for relatively slight variants, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:142091" authority="Emery" authorityName="Emery" class="Hexapoda" family="Formicidae" genus="Neoponera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Neoponera apicalis var. verenae Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="variety" species="apicalis" variety="verenae">verenae</taxonomicName>
from Panama as a variety of 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33218" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla apicalis (Latreille)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apicalis">apicalis</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:141776" authority="Emery" authorityName="Emery" class="Hexapoda" family="Formicidae" genus="Neoponera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Neoponera obscuricornis r. latocciput Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="obscuricornis" subSpecies="latocciput">latocciput</taxonomicName>
from Ecuador as a race of 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33337" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla obscuricornis Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obscuricornis">obscuricornis</taxonomicName>
. Why he assigned 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:141776" authority="Emery" authorityName="Emery" class="Hexapoda" family="Formicidae" genus="Neoponera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Neoponera obscuricornis r. latocciput Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="obscuricornis" subSpecies="latocciput">latocciput</taxonomicName>
to 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33337" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla obscuricornis Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obscuricornis">obscuricornis</taxonomicName>
instead of 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:142090" authority="Emery" authorityName="Emery" class="Hexapoda" family="Formicidae" genus="Neoponera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Neoponera latreillei Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="latreillei">latreillei</taxonomicName>
is not clear, all the more so since he acknowledges both taxa in the brief description. It is apparent, however, that he put more consideration into form than coloration.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="15">
Brown’s (1957) primary contribution was the realization that Latreille’s original description of 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:147699" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Formica" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Formica apicalis Latreille" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apicalis">Formica apicalis</taxonomicName>
matched the species that Forel and Emery had been calling first 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:186734" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla flavicornis (Fabricius)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavicornis">flavicornis</taxonomicName>
and then 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:142090" authority="Emery" authorityName="Emery" class="Hexapoda" family="Formicidae" genus="Neoponera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Neoponera latreillei Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="latreillei">latreillei</taxonomicName>
. He put these into synonymy under 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33218" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla apicalis (Latreille)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apicalis">apicalis</taxonomicName>
. Brown evidently did not examine relevant specimens in either Forel or Emery’s collections, however, so he did not know that Emery and Forel used the name apicalis in a sense opposite to his own. This led him to infer erroneously that Forel’s 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:142091" authority="Emery" authorityName="Emery" class="Hexapoda" family="Formicidae" genus="Neoponera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Neoponera apicalis var. verenae Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="variety" species="apicalis" variety="verenae">Neoponera apicalis var. verenae</taxonomicName>
must be a variety of Latreille’s 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33218" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla apicalis (Latreille)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apicalis">apicalis</taxonomicName>
instead of the oldest available name for the species with the marginate petiole.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="15">
Brown apparently did not see sufficient South American material prior to his 1957 publication to uncover the rarer species 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33337" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla obscuricornis Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obscuricornis">P. obscuricornis</taxonomicName>
, as he lays out a case for the existence of “two and only two species” (Brown 1957, pg 231). Brown’s two species, “ 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33218" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla apicalis (Latreille)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apicalis">apicalis</taxonomicName>
” and “ 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33337" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla obscuricornis Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obscuricornis">obscuricornis</taxonomicName>
”, are unambiguously 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33218" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla apicalis (Latreille)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apicalis">apicalis Latreille</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:186243" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla verenae (Forel)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="verenae">verenae Forel</taxonomicName>
. Under his two-species dichotomy, Brown argued in the absence of type material that Emery’s 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:141777" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla flavicornis var. obscuricornis Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="variety" species="flavicornis" variety="obscuricornis">obscuricornis</taxonomicName>
could not be 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33218" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla apicalis (Latreille)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apicalis">apicalis</taxonomicName>
because of the antennal coloration. By default he treated it as the valid name for the other widespread species (
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:186243" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla verenae (Forel)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="verenae">P. verenae [Forel]</taxonomicName>
in the present study). Apparently Brown did arrive much later at a three-species conclusion that was never published, although it is unlikely he recognized the third species as being Emery’s 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33337" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla obscuricornis Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obscuricornis">obscuricornis</taxonomicName>
(C. R. F. 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Brandão">Brandao</normalizedToken>
, pers. comm).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="15">
Brown’s reorganization was perpetuated in an unpublished but widely circulated manuscript key to Neotropical 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24842" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla Smith" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Pachycondyla</taxonomicName>
. Consequently, the common species 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:186243" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla verenae (Forel)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="verenae">P. verenae</taxonomicName>
has been misdiagnosed consistently as 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33337" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla obscuricornis Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obscuricornis">P. obscuricornis</taxonomicName>
in the literature and in museum collections. In those cases where voucher specimens of “ 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33337" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla obscuricornis Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obscuricornis">obscuricornis</taxonomicName>
” were available in this study (Kempf 1972, Duelli &amp; Duelli-Klein 1976, Wild 2003, Longino 2004), as well as in Traniello and 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Hölldobler">Hoelldobler</normalizedToken>
(1984) which contained sufficiently detailed photographs, all records actually pertain to 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:186243" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla verenae (Forel)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="verenae">P. verenae</taxonomicName>
. Since there are no collection records of true 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33337" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla obscuricornis Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obscuricornis">P. obscuricornis</taxonomicName>
from Central America, it is almost certain that other MesoAmerican studies of “ 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33337" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla obscuricornis Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obscuricornis">obscuricornis</taxonomicName>
” (e.g., Fresneau 1984, Oliveira &amp; 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Hölldobler">Hoelldobler</normalizedToken>
1991, Lommelen et al 2002) also pertain to 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:186243" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla verenae (Forel)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="verenae">P. verenae</taxonomicName>
. More ambiguous are South American references (e.g., Wheeler et al 1999, 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Düssman">Duessman</normalizedToken>
et al 1996). Given the relative rarity of true 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33337" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla obscuricornis Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obscuricornis">P. obscuricornis</taxonomicName>
, most South American records may also refer to 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:186243" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla verenae (Forel)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="verenae">P. verenae</taxonomicName>
, but the identity of these cannot be verified without the examination of specimens.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="15">
Unfortunately, taxonomic instability may continue to persist for some time in the 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33218" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla apicalis (Latreille)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apicalis">Pachycondyla apicalis</taxonomicName>
complex. While the species-level nomenclature may stabilize with the recognition of three species, it is almost certain that the heterogeneous genus 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24842" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla Smith" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Pachycondyla</taxonomicName>
is paraphyletic with respect to much of the rest of the tribe 
<taxonomicName pageNumber="16" rank="tribe" tribe="Ponerini">Ponerini</taxonomicName>
(C. Schmidt, unpublished molecular data). As generic taxonomy falls in line with new phylogenetic hypotheses, it is entirely possible that various generic names, including 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:147137" authority="Emery" authorityName="Emery" class="Hexapoda" family="Formicidae" genus="Neoponera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Neoponera Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Neoponera</taxonomicName>
for the species discussed here, will be resurrected to retain monophyly of the ponerine genera.
</paragraph>
